      <h1>Misogi (禊)</h1>
      <p class="concept-hero-subtitle">One of the central subjects of our school: not folklore or mood, but the rigorous clearing of breath, attention, intention, and character so technique remains true under pressure.</p>
    </div>

    <p class="news-meta">April 4, 2026</p>

    <p>
      Misogi is often discussed too quickly and too vaguely.
      Some reduce it to an image of ritual purification,
      some to an exotic Japanese curiosity,
      and others to loose “spirituality” that supposedly sits beside technique.
      <strong>In our line, that is a basic error.
      Misogi is not an accessory to Aikido.
      It is one of the practices meant to remove what corrupts a person in action:
      chaotic breathing, scattered attention, ego reaction,
      collapsing posture, and lack of honesty toward one’s own limits.</strong>
    </p>

    <p>
      That is exactly why this subject matters so much in our school.
      If Aikido is understood only as a set of techniques,
      then we can talk about locks, entries, throws, and timing.
      But if it is understood as a budō path,
      then one question becomes unavoidable: <em>what happens to the person under pressure</em>?
      Does breath remain intact?
      Does center remain intact?
      Does decision remain intact?
      Does ethics remain intact?
      Misogi addresses precisely that level.
    </p>

    <h2>What does “Misogi” actually mean?</h2>
    <p>
      The term itself has roots in Japanese purification practice
      and historically is associated with religious and ritual forms [1].
      That is an important starting point, but only a starting point.
      In budō, and especially in our line,
      the point is not to collect symbols.
      The practical meaning is clearer:
      <strong>purification means removing what clouds correct action</strong>.
      Sometimes that is excess tension.
      Sometimes fear.
      Sometimes haste.
      Sometimes pride.
      Sometimes the collapse of breathing,
      which causes technique to lose quality after only a few repetitions.
    </p>

    <p>
      Because of that, two extremes should be rejected immediately.
      The first says: “misogi is only an old ritual.”
      The second says: “misogi is so intangible that it cannot be trained concretely.”
      Both are convenient, and both are false.
      Misogi has historical roots, but it also has a hard operational meaning.
      In practice, it means restoring order where a person begins to break down
      under effort, tempo, or pressure.
    </p>

    <h2>Ichikukai: the severe source of this practice</h2>
    <p>
      To understand why misogi occupies such an important place in Toyoda’s line,
      we have to return to Ichikukai.
      This was not a place of atmosphere.
      It was a place of severe shugyō.
      The history of Ichikukai shows that the practice there was built from the beginning
      as a parallel path of <strong>Zen and Misogi trained together</strong>,
      not as two separate worlds [2].
    </p>

    <p>
      What matters here is that in Ichikukai’s own historical account,
      “misogi” does not mainly mean the popular image of standing under an icy waterfall.
      The dojo’s history explains directly that the training consisted of intense,
      repeated loud chanting of the formula <em>TO HO KA MI E MI TA ME</em>,
      under conditions of high effort, discipline, and psychophysical load [2].
      That matters because it immediately clears away the cheap folkloric picture.
      The heart of the practice was not visual drama.
      The heart of the practice was purification through rigor,
      repetition, breath, endurance, and brutally honest exposure to one’s own weakness.
    </p>

    <p>
      In that sense, Ichikukai teaches something very modern:
      a person is not purified by talking about balance,
      but by entering a practice that exposes disorder.
      As fatigue rises,
      everything becomes visible: chaotic breathing,
      unstable attention, inner fragmentation,
      the urge to escape, anger, theatricality, and ego.
      <strong>Misogi is not pretending to be pure.
      It is going through training severe enough
      that your inner disorder cannot stay hidden for long.</strong>
    </p>

    <h2>Why Misogi is so important in Toyoda’s style</h2>
    <p>
      Fumio Toyoda’s biography on our site and the AAA organizational materials
      make one thing very clear:
      this theme did not appear at the margins of his path [3][4].
      Toyoda began misogi training at age seventeen at Ichikukai Dojo,
      then lived there for several years while also beginning Zen practice [3][4].
      That means something simple:
      in his formation, Aikido technique,
      breath, inner discipline, and purifying practice
      formed one system from the beginning.
    </p>

    <p>
      That is what separates serious understanding of misogi from decorative understanding.
      For Toyoda, it was not an “Aikido-adjacent” topic.
      It was part of the forge
      in which the conditions for real technique were built.
      Without that,
      Aikido easily decays into elegant choreography:
      pretty movement without a real axis,
      softness without center,
      fluidity without responsibility,
      calmness that disappears under the first serious load.
    </p>

    <p>
      In Toyoda’s style, misogi is fundamental because it orders four things at once:
    </p>
    <ul>
      <li><strong>breath</strong> — so movement does not collapse under fatigue,</li>
      <li><strong>attention</strong> — so the practitioner sees what is actually happening in contact,</li>
      <li><strong>intention</strong> — so technique is not just accidental reaction,</li>
      <li><strong>character</strong> — so correction, effort, and pressure do not immediately trigger ego defense.</li>
    </ul>

    <h2>Misogi does not replace technique — it clears technique</h2>
    <p>
      This must be stated plainly,
      because this subject easily produces opposite mistakes.
      The first is made by people who think
      it is enough to “know techniques” and the rest will solve itself.
      The second is made by those who escape into breath,
      mood, or metaphysical language while neglecting craft.
      Both roads fail.
    </p>

    <p>
      <strong>Misogi is not a substitute for technique.
      It makes honest technique possible.</strong>
      If posture breaks,
      shoulders rise,
      breath becomes fragmented,
      the practitioner starts guessing instead of leading,
      and after a few repetitions only wants to “survive the set,”
      then the problem is not only shape of movement.
      The problem is state.
      Misogi is what works on that level.
    </p>

    <h2>What absence of Misogi looks like on the mat</h2>
    <ul>
      <li><strong>Breath collapses under pace:</strong> the first repetitions may look correct, but quality falls apart as load rises.</li>
      <li><strong>The mind reacts instead of leading:</strong> the practitioner guesses, rushes, and repairs movement too late.</li>
      <li><strong>Defensive tension appears:</strong> shoulders and arms take over while center stops organizing the body.</li>
      <li><strong>Form starts hiding weakness:</strong> lots of apparent fluidity, little real control of axis and direction.</li>
      <li><strong>Correction becomes irritating:</strong> instead of implementation, there is explanation, frustration, or empty agreement without change.</li>
      <li><strong>The partner becomes an ego problem:</strong> difficult contact stops being material for learning and becomes a battle over self-image.</li>
    </ul>

    <p>
      All of these are concrete signs.
      There is no need to speak about misogi in abstraction.
      Just watch what happens when fatigue,
      complexity, or pressure rise.
      If quality disappears immediately,
      then the foundation has not yet been cleared and stabilized.
    </p>

    <h2>How Misogi appears in mature dojo practice</h2>
    <ul>
      <li><strong>In breath:</strong> exhalation stabilizes rhythm, center, and decision rather than serving as decoration.</li>
      <li><strong>In repeatability:</strong> the tenth repetition does not collapse compared to the first.</li>
      <li><strong>In correction:</strong> attention returns to the task faster than ego can build a defense.</li>
      <li><strong>In partner work:</strong> the practitioner does not escape into brute force or soft chaos, but maintains clear intention and responsibility.</li>
      <li><strong>In mental posture:</strong> difficulty does not destroy direction; it reveals what still requires work.</li>
      <li><strong>In simplicity:</strong> less theater, less unnecessary movement, more axis, decision, and discipline.</li>
    </ul>

    <p>
      Understood this way, misogi does not turn someone into a “mystic.”
      It turns them into a practitioner who is less chaotic,
      more present, and harder to break under pressure.
      That has direct impact on Aikido quality.
    </p>

    <h2>Why this is one of the most important subjects in our school</h2>
    <p>
      Our school does not want to preserve only the outer shape of techniques.
      If a line is to remain alive,
      it must preserve the method that feeds those techniques.
      That is where misogi becomes central.
      It reminds us that transmission is not only about technique names,
      exam order, or visual aesthetics.
      Transmission also includes the quality of the person
      who performs and teaches the technique.
    </p>

    <p>
      That is why, in our perspective,
      misogi is not some secondary “spiritual theme.”
      It is a practice of responsibility.
      It teaches us not to hide behind pose,
      not to confuse emotional agitation with energy,
      not to confuse softness with collapse,
      and not to confuse calmness with passivity.
      It orders the relationship between body,
      breath, attention, and decision.
      Without that relationship,
      durable budō is very hard to claim.
    </p>

    <h2>Living transmission: Toyoda, Tajiri Sensei, and Germanov Sensei</h2>
    <p>
      For POA, misogi is not a museum subject.
      The importance of this practice was strongly anchored by Toyoda,
      whose own formation passed through the severe environment of Ichikukai,
      with Zen and Aikido trained as one process [3][4].
      Yet this emphasis on inner rigor,
      disciplined breathing, and purification of intention
      does not end with his biography.
    </p>

    <p>
      In our line of transmission,
      this remains a living subject carried forward by Germanov Sensei,
      who after Toyoda’s passing continues his path,
      preserving the connection between technique,
      Zen practice, and inner discipline [5].
      The relation to Tajiri Sensei is also important here,
      as part of the continuing Japanese transmission surrounding this line.
      So this is not about repeating the word “misogi” as a slogan.
      It is about preserving a concrete quality of work:
      rigor, state-clearing, order in action,
      and responsibility for what is actually being transmitted to students.
    </p>

    <p>
      This must be emphasized clearly:
      transmission is honest only when it carries not just techniques,
      but also a way of forming the person.
      If only outer form remains,
      while breath, discipline, inner work, and ethics in action are lost,
      then only a shell remains.
      Misogi is one of the tests
      of whether the core of the transmission is still alive.
    </p>

    <h2>How to train Misogi today without exoticism or pretending</h2>
    <p>
      Not everyone will train in the exact historical formula of Ichikukai.
      That is not the main point.
      The principle is the main point.
      In a modern dojo and outside it,
      it can still be trained concretely:
    </p>
    <ul>
      <li><strong>Daily breath practice:</strong> 5–10 minutes of quiet sitting, longer exhalation, and observation of unnecessary tension.</li>
      <li><strong>Repeatability under light fatigue:</strong> do not stop at the first good entry; test whether quality remains over further rounds.</li>
      <li><strong>Reset after error:</strong> exhale, correct posture, return to the task without drama and without theatrical self-condemnation.</li>
      <li><strong>Voice and rhythm work:</strong> kiai, counting, or shared rhythm can expose collapse of breath, tempo, and concentration.</li>
      <li><strong>One task per training session:</strong> for example, “do not lose exhalation on entry” or “do not harden the shoulders during faster series.”</li>
      <li><strong>Self-reflection after class:</strong> where chaos appeared, where pride entered, where breathing stopped leading movement.</li>
    </ul>

    <p>
      These are not “less spiritual” versions of misogi.
      They are often its more honest versions.
      Less spectacular,
      but much closer to the daily work of an actual practitioner.
      Misogi matures through regularity,
      not through a single intense experience.
    </p>

    <h2>Misogi beyond the dojo</h2>
    <p>
      If practice is real,
      its traces must also appear beyond the mat.
      At work, misogi means that pressure does not hijack the whole decision system.
      In conversation, it means not responding only from wounded ego.
      In leadership, it means pressure does not turn responsibility into chaos.
    </p>

    <p>
      This is still not magic.
      It is hygiene of state.
      A person who has truly worked through misogi
      does not automatically become calm, wise, and perfect.
      But they do become quicker to recognize their own tension,
      less likely to collapse under pressure,
      and more responsible for the effects of their actions.
      That is already a great deal.
    </p>

    <h2>Most common misreadings</h2>
    <ul>
      <li><strong>“Misogi is only a purification ritual”:</strong> no. Historical roots matter, but in budō the point is purification of state and action.</li>
      <li><strong>“Misogi = waterfall”:</strong> no. In the Ichikukai tradition, severe work with voice, breath, effort, and discipline was also central [2].</li>
      <li><strong>“This is a soft, non-technical topic”:</strong> no. Breath quality, axis, attention, and intention directly affect technique.</li>
      <li><strong>“Meditation alone is enough”:</strong> no. Misogi must be tested in movement, correction, effort, tempo, and partner work.</li>
      <li><strong>“This belongs only to old masters”:</strong> no. In our line, it remains part of living transmission and school responsibility.</li>
    </ul>

    <h2>Conclusion</h2>
    <p>
      Misogi is one of the most important subjects in our school
      because it addresses the foundation without which everything else becomes form alone.
      It is the practice of clearing breath,
      attention, intention, and character.
      It is training in removing the chaos
      that corrupts both technique and the person performing it.
      It is also one of the clearest places where Toyoda’s style becomes visible:
      Aikido, Zen, and inner discipline
      not as three hobbies,
      but as one system for shaping action.
    </p>

    <p>
      That is why misogi must be treated seriously.
      Not as ornament.
      Not as legend.
      Not as a slogan for creating atmosphere.
      But as a task.
      Daily,
      demanding,
      often uncomfortable,
      but absolutely central
      if we want to preserve the living core of this line of transmission.
    </p>

